04107nam a22005775i 9780292763784DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211993txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927637847 a10.7560/7467702doi  a(DE-B1597)588714  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aLev, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Euro-American Cinema /cPeter Lev. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. HISTORY AND THEORY -- t1. The Art Film -- t2. Economic Links -- t3. The Euro-American Art Film: Definition -- t4. The Euro-American Art Film: History -- t5. Cultural Dominance or Cultural Mix -- tPart II: Case Studies -- tIntroduction -- t6. Art and Commerce in Contempt -- t7. Blow-Up, Swinging London, and the Film Generation -- t8. Pasolini's The Canterbury Tales: The Estrangement of an English Classic -- t9. Paris, Texas, an American Dream -- t10. The Last Emperor: Pleasures and Dangers of the Exotic -- t11. Final Comments -- tNotes -- tFilmography: Euro-American Art Films -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith McDonalds in Moscow and Disneyland in Paris and Tokyo, American popular culture is spreading around the globe. Regional, national, and ethnic cultures are being powerfully affected by competition from American values and American popular forms. This literate and lively study explores the spread of American culture into international cinema as reflected by the collision and partial merger of two important styles of filmmaking: the Hollywood style of stars, genres, and action, and the European art film style of ambiguity, authorial commentary, and borrowings from other arts. Peter Lev departs from the traditional approach of national cinema histories and discusses some of the blends, overlaps, and hegemonies that are typical of the world film industry of recent years. In Part One, he gives a historical and theoretical overview of what he terms the "Euro-American art film," which is characterized by prominent use of the English language, a European art film director, cast and crew from at least two countries, and a stylistic mixing of European art film and American entertainment. The second part of Lev’s study examines in detail five examples of the Euro-American art film: Contempt (1963), Blow-Up (1966), The Canterbury Tales (1972), Paris, Texas (1983), and The Last Emperor (1987). These case studies reveal that the European art film has had a strong influence on world cinema and that many Euro-American films are truly cultural blends rather than abject takeovers by Hollywood cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74677040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292763784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292763784/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK